{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":206578,"duration_api_ms":223460,"ttft_ms":56624,"num_turns":4,"result":"I've grounded the two load-bearing empirical claims. Now my single Critique-mode idea record.\n\nThe searches confirm the two facts the critique rests on: (1) Laukkonen and Slagter model deconstructive meditation as relaxing precision and reducing abstract/deep processing of a self that is treated as a generative model, and (2) the Free Energy Principle, on Friston's own deflationary reading, is officially agnostic or \"as-if\" about personal-level inference (agents \"do not minimize anything\"; it has been charged with \"confusion of description and explanation\"). That is exactly the seam the frontier's claim ignores.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The Brain Model Already Took a Side\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Mode: Critique. The active frontier claims the Free Energy Principle, applied to contemplative self-negation, formally reproduces the atman/anatta dispute at a higher level of abstraction. This record tests and narrows that claim.\",\n    \"Thinking method source: Advaita neti-neti negation, used as a lens by refusing to accept the first available redescription (here, the predictive-processing redescription) as the final account. Critique of the lens: neti-neti can itself smuggle in a residual knower, so it was checked against Bahiya-style refusal of any settling place.\",\n    \"Primary text comparison one: Shankara, adhyasa-bhasya (preamble to the Brahma Sutra Bhasya), where the witnessing self is the presupposition of all knowing and superimposition and is svaprakasha, self-luminous, not established by any means of knowledge or inference.\",\n    \"Primary text comparison two: SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta and Udana 1.10 Bahiya Sutta, where even consciousness is to be regarded as not-self and where, in the seen, there is only the seen, with no knower authorized to settle there.\",\n    \"Laukkonen and Slagter, From many to (n)one: Meditation and the plasticity of the predictive mind, Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews 128 (2021), which models deconstructive meditation as relaxing precision weighting and reducing temporally deep, abstract processing of the self-model.\",\n    \"Friston, the Free Energy Principle, on the deflationary reading where agents do not literally minimize anything and behavior is only interpretable as free-energy minimization; plus the standard charge that the framework confuses description with explanation and is agnostic between personal and subpersonal levels.\",\n    \"Near-neighbor prior art named by the frontier: Matthias Rose and Prakasa, Phenomenology and the Cognitive Sciences, that Advaita treats consciousness as directly self-disclosing rather than inferred; Stanford Encyclopedia entry on Shankara; Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy.\",\n    \"Prior Lumenary records this narrows: The Inferential Gap, and the inference-policy to residual-warrant revision already noted in the concept graph.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-pew-where-americans-find-meaning-in-life and modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory, for meaning loss and isolated overinterpretation.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"The predictive-processing account of self-negation does not neutrally reproduce the atman versus not-self dispute; it has quietly joined one side. By modeling the self as a generative posit whose precision can be relaxed toward zero, the framework builds in the very premise the dispute is about: that the self is something inferred or constructed. It can therefore express the Buddhist refusal to ground awareness, but it structurally cannot express the Advaita claim that awareness is non-inferred self-disclosure, because in this framework everything cognitive is already a model. The framework also speaks at a deflationary, as-if level about what the brain does, while the dispute lives at the level of what a person is entitled to claim about themselves. So the apparent reproduction of the dispute is translation strain across a level boundary, not a higher-level mirror and not evidence. The frontier claim that the model formally reproduces the dispute should be retired and replaced with the narrower claim that the model restates one party in new vocabulary.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Prior work treated the predictive-processing framing as a neutral higher-level mirror in which the old dispute reappears. The distinct move here is that the mirror is bent twice over. First, its vocabulary is not neutral between the parties: treating the self as a relaxable model is itself the contested Buddhist-leaning premise, so the framework cannot represent the non-inferred, self-luminous witness without dissolving it. Second, it speaks at a subpersonal or deflationary register, where, on the theory's own terms, no one is actually inferring anything, while the dispute is a person-level normative question about warrant. Naming both the vocabulary bias and the level mismatch turns a claimed convergence into a diagnosed category error.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The critique may attack a position no one defends. Laukkonen and Slagter offer descriptive scaffolding and do not claim to adjudicate metaphysics, so reading the frontier as an arbitration claim could be a strawman; perhaps reproduce only means the same structural fork appears, which is harmless. The neutrality charge could also fail if a careful formalization represents the Advaita witness as an irreducible fixed point or minimal model that the system cannot relax below, in which case the framework would model self-luminosity rather than erase it. Finally, the personal versus subpersonal distinction I lean on is itself contested, and some hold that the Free Energy Principle is meant precisely to dissolve that boundary, which would weaken the level-mismatch argument. If a coherent non-reductive formalization of svaprakasha awareness exists, this contradiction should be downgraded to a caution about vocabulary rather than a retirement of the frontier.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\n    \"textual\",\n    \"interpretive\",\n    \"empirical-adjacent\",\n    \"analogical\",\n    \"speculative\"\n  ],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.55,\n    \"generativity\": 0.8,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.66,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.83,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.79,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.6,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.68,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.87,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.7,\n    \"publishability\": 0.66\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this contradiction is right, then a formal predictive-processing model that tries to represent the Advaita witness should either reduce it to a low-precision posit or require an element outside the modeling hierarchy. If a clean formalization represents non-inferred self-luminous awareness without reducing it to a model, the neutrality charge is weakened.\",\n    \"If this contradiction is right, then practitioners given a self is just a model explanation after objectless states should more often report the framing as confirming emptiness or no-self than as confirming a true Self, because the vocabulary already leans one way. If reports split evenly or lean toward true-Self conclusions, the vocabulary-bias claim is weakened.\",\n    \"Close-read Shankara on svaprakasha and the witness as presupposition against Friston's deflationary statements that agents do not minimize anything, and test whether the dispute and the framework are even predicating of the same subject.\",\n    \"Search whether the personal versus subpersonal critique of the Free Energy Principle has already been aimed specifically at meditation and the self, in Metzinger, Sebastian, Limanowski, or Sanchez-Canizares, before treating the level-mismatch point as new.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before accepting any scientific redescription of a contemplative claim, ask at what level the redescription speaks and whether its vocabulary has already decided the question it claims to neutrally restate.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"A Mechanism Describes; It Does Not Decide\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"A model of how your mind goes quiet cannot tell you what you are.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"An account of what the brain does during a quiet or objectless state describes a mechanism. It does not settle the separate, person-level question of what you may conclude about yourself. Do not let the description quietly answer the question.\",\n    \"body\": \"After a deep quiet, the mind wants a verdict: I am nothing, or I am the true Self, or I have seen through the self. A neat scientific story can arrive and seem to hand you the answer. Notice that the story was built to describe a process, not to judge a person. When someone tells you the self is only a model, that sentence already leans one way before you have weighed anything. Hold the description and the verdict apart. Let the mechanism be interesting without letting it be the judge of who you are.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Meaning loss and identity distress when a quiet or objectless practice experience is handed a verdict by a borrowed scientific story, producing either nihilistic deflation or spiritual inflation.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Psychologically stable adults in secular mindfulness, non-dual, or app-based practice who interpret their experiences through popular neuroscience and reach for what it really proves about the self.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survives the contrast between Shankara's non-inferred self-luminous witness and the Buddhist refusal to ground awareness, by showing that a predictive-processing redescription can voice only one side and speaks at a level where no person is making a claim at all.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if a non-reductive scientific model can genuinely represent both the witness and not-self without favoring either, or if separating mechanism from verdict makes no difference to how people interpret and recover from destabilizing states.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"critique-mode\",\n      \"predictive-processing\",\n      \"atman-anatta\",\n      \"objectless-awareness\",\n      \"meaning-loss\",\n      \"overinterpretation\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Separate the Mechanism From the Verdict\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"When a story explains what your experience really means about you, split the two claims it is making.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To stop a scientific or app-given explanation of a quiet practice state from silently deciding an identity question it was never built to answer.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Identity distress and meaning loss after objectless or depersonalization-adjacent practice states, intensified by borrowed explanations that feel like proof about the self.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Stable adults who meditate or practice self-inquiry, often through apps or popular science, and who tend to intellectualize their experiences into conclusions about who they are.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for people in active depersonalization or derealization disorder, psychosis, mania, acute dissociation, or trauma activation, who need clinical care rather than an epistemic exercise. Not for beginners with no destabilizing experiences to interpret.\",\n    \"duration\": \"8 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Only after an unusually quiet, blank, or self-loosening experience, no more than twice per week.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Try it after three separate such experiences before judging whether it helps.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Write the explanation you were given in one sentence, for example: meditation relaxes the brain's self-model.\",\n      \"Underline the part that is a mechanism claim: what the brain or mind did.\",\n      \"Underline separately the part that is an identity verdict: what you supposedly are, or are not.\",\n      \"Ask whether the mechanism claim, even if true, actually forces the verdict, or whether the verdict was added.\",\n      \"For the next 24 hours, hold the mechanism as interesting and leave the verdict open. Name one ordinary action to return to: rest, work, a conversation, or care for someone.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether the experience stays meaningful when you refuse to draw a final conclusion about yourself.\",\n      \"Whether the borrowed explanation was leaning toward one conclusion before you weighed anything.\",\n      \"Whether holding the verdict open lowers both the deflation and the inflation.\",\n      \"Whether the exercise turns into more rumination rather than less.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Stop if this increases obsessive analysis, derealization, fear about your own mind, or shame. Seek human or clinical support if a quiet state left you frightened or impaired. This is not a substitute for care.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It weakens if people report more rumination or detachment, if ordinary rest and conversation help just as much, or if separating mechanism from verdict makes no difference to distress after three attempts.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"mechanism-versus-verdict\",\n      \"objectless-awareness\",\n      \"meaning-loss\",\n      \"low-risk\",\n      \"secular-mindfulness\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Level-Mismatch Prior-Art Search\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the contribution is distinct, the personal versus subpersonal critique of the Free Energy Principle will exist in general philosophy of mind, but not aimed specifically at the claim that predictive processing neutrally reproduces the atman and not-self dispute. If that exact application already exists, novelty should fall below 0.35.\",\n      \"result\": \"Initial search confirmed strong general near-neighbors: Friston's own deflationary reading, and published charges that the framework confuses description with explanation and is agnostic across levels. The specific application to the atman and not-self neutrality claim was not found in this pass, but the audit is incomplete.\",\n      \"impact\": \"revises\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Search Metzinger, Sebastian, Limanowski, Sanchez-Canizares, and Sharf for the level critique applied to meditation and selfhood before raising novelty.\",\n      \"status\": \"complete\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Can the Framework Hold the Witness\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If a coherent predictive-processing formalization can represent non-inferred, self-luminous awareness as an irreducible element that the system cannot relax below, without reducing it to a low-precision posit, then the neutrality charge fails and this contradiction should be downgraded to a vocabulary caution.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Examine whether any deep-self or minimal-self predictive model treats baseline awareness as outside the generative hierarchy rather than as its lowest layer, and test it against Shankara's svaprakasha.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Mechanism-Verdict Split Trial\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For the target cohort, separating the mechanism claim from the identity verdict after a quiet or objectless state should reduce both nihilistic deflation and inflation, and reduce the urge to draw a final self-conclusion. If it increases rumination or does no better than ordinary rest and conversation, the practice is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Run a small screened self-report trial with stable app or self-inquiry practitioners who recently received a self is just a model style explanation, with explicit exclusion of clinical cases.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Vocabulary-Lean Cross Check\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the framework's vocabulary already leans one way, then practitioners given the same predictive-processing explanation of an objectless state should more often conclude emptiness or no-self than a true Self. If conclusions split evenly or favor true-Self readings, the vocabulary-bias claim is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Design a vignette study presenting one neutral and one predictive-processing explanation of an objectless state, and code which self-conclusion each elicits.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nSources used to ground this record:\n- [Laukkonen and Slagter, From many to (n)one (ScienceDirect)](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S014976342100261X)\n- [Self-supervision, normativity and the free energy principle (Synthese)](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11229-020-02622-2)\n- [Free energy principle (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_energy_principle)","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"63860abe-dae7-4f45-bb2f-1d9f1a9414b9","total_cost_usd":3.6008195000000005,"usage":{"input_tokens":3776,"cache_creation_input_tokens":466766,"cache_read_input_tokens":286392,"output_tokens":12626,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":466766,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"no